content.description: SDS at jugs and work out right and then back left onto the smooth brown slab using nice but sharp incut edges and the occasional pocket, the largest being called " Tinkerbell's Anus". Interesting moves on great rock.
content.location: Right side of the west face.

content.description: SDS and climb interesting finger pockets up the short varnished face - too bad it's not longer.
content.location: Center of the north face on the eastern half of the boulder.

content.description:
SDS at twin slots on an arete and power out the smooth, rounded bulge to a smooth but positive dish then grab a jug and top it out. Short but powerful and tough for the grade.

Can be done from a standing start at about V0-.
content.location: Southeast arete of the eastern boulder.

content.description: Climbs the nice slab on excellent rock with one hard move at the bottom as you get established on the slab.
content.location: The center of the north face on the western half of the boulder.

content.description: Lieback your way up the offset seam that transitions from slightly overhanging to a slab. The crux is a tricky section midway with thin edges as you work your feet to the lip.

SDS below the short arete and lieback/palm your way up to the top with the crux coming right at the start.

This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
content.location:
Just right of

The Three Mulleteers

at the left-slanting arete.

content.description: Start matched from a pointy jug below a smooth bulge and fire up and left to a flat edge before moving back right to finish on incut edges. This is a nice problem on very good rock.
content.protection: Pad & maybe a spotter to keep you off the rock directly behind the problem.
content.location: Left side of the south face.

content.description: Up the smooth, swirly slab on dark patina with nice edges. The crux is the first move or so getting established on the slab.
content.location: The left edge of the north face on the western half of the boulder.

content.description:
SDS with a left hand edge and right hand jug under the bulge and make one powerful move up to a good pocket and finish up

The Three Mulleteers

.
content.location:
Starts just left of

The Three Mulleteers

at the arete.

content.description: SDS at a low jug and oooze over the bulge to fingery edges over the lip. Work your feet up and finish up the nice patina slab.
content.protection: pad, spotter to keep you off the rock to the left.
content.location: Left side of the west face.

content.description: SDS on the block at the base with hands on a hidden undercling hold. Reach out to the lip and then match higher up and pull onto the slab above taking care not to fall back onto the boulder at the base. The moves are fairly secure but falling is probably best avoided on this problem.
content.location: The right side of the north face on the western half of the boulder where it's undercut.

content.description:
Start from a left-slanting rail and climb crispy edges up the short face to incut jugs at the top and mantel over to finish.

This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
content.location:
The light-colored face around and left of

Poker in the Front

.

climbs.name: Business Up Front, Party in the Back

content.description:
Work up the shallow corner system to jugs on an arete. The crux is early on and it gets easier the higher you go.

This problem isn't listed in the Joshua Tree Bouldering Guide but is an obvious line with some good moves that's worth a go when in the area.
content.location:
The shallow corner just right of

Poker in the Front

.

climbs.name: A Mullet, a 12" Cord and a V13 Ability

content.description: Climb jugs and incut buckets past a handjam to a high finish. Fairly solid but pull gently as a few holds seem suspect and falling is best avoided.
content.protection: pads, spotter to keep you off the block at the base.
content.location: Right side of the south face of the western boulder.
